                {
                    "title": "<span style=\"font-size:26px;\">&nbsp;</span>",
                    "content": "<div class=\"footnotes\">\n<h5>Footnotes</h5>\n<ol>\n<li>See <a href=\"https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/pub/75-004-m/75-004-m2019004-eng.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Statistics Canada, Center for Gender, Diversity and Inclusion, The gender wage gap in Canada: 1998 to 2018, October 2019</a>. (\u21e1 back to text)</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/t1/tbl1/en/tv.action?pid=1410006401\" target=\"_blank\">Statistics Canada, Employee wages by industry, annual, table no. 14-10-0064-01</a>. (\u21e1 back to text)</li>\n<li>The study focused on <a href=\"https://www.stata-journal.com/article.html?article=st0151\" target=\"_blank\">Blinder-Oaxaca decomposition</a>, a well-known statistical method used to determine how much of a wage gap between two groups can be explained by various control factors. (\u21e1 back to text)</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www120.statcan.gc.ca/stcsr/en/sr1/srs?fq=stclac%3A2&amp;q=table+14-10-0064&amp;wb-srch-sub=02\" target=\"_blank\">Statistics Canada, Average and median gender wage ratio, annual, table 14-10-0064</a>. (\u21e1 back to text)</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n",
